The Telegraph - Calcutta

 Security blanket over Salt Lake Stadium

A STAFF REPORTER

Calcutta: A security blanket has been thrown over the Salt Lake Stadium on the eve of Prime Minister Manmohan Singh?s visit Wednesday. A section of policemen took up position at different points in and around the stadium from Tuesday night. 

According to police, there will be 1,500 policemen on Wednesday. 

?The security arrangement has been made according to the guideline given by the Special Protection Group (SPG), the agency that looks after PM?s security,? said Parveen Kumar, superintendent of police, North 24-Parganas. 

According to the police, the Eastern Metropolitan Bypass stretch from Science City to the Stadium will be closed for vehicular movement for 15 minutes before the PM?s arrival and departure. 

Elaborating on police arrangement, an official said: ?Apart from the policemen of State Armed Police (SAP), a large contingent of Rapid Action Force (RAF) and Eastern Frontier Rifle (EFR) will also be deployed in and around the stadium. 

Sniffer dogs were brought to check the ground and gallery on Tuesday. The exercise will be repeated Wednesday morning.? 

Senior officials of the state Intelligence Branch (IB) visited the stadium Monday. ?We have suggested to the police to check all the entry and exit points of stadium thoroughly from Tuesday night. 

Besides, all vehicles entering and coming out from Salt Lake will have to go through a security-check on from Wednesday morning,? said an IB official. 

Police, however, said that there would be some last minute changes. ?SPG decides at the last stage and they don?t discuss it with us,? said an official. 

